        "title": "Integration gaps not covered by any skeleton above",
        "content": "These need real (or `respx`-recorded) network fixtures and are worth flagging even without a runnable skeleton:\n\n1. **End-to-end pipeline against a live ATS** — `run_sync` wired to one real `sources.yaml` entry per platform, run against recorded HTTP cassettes, to catch schema drift (e.g., Meta's `doc_id` rotation, which is already a known recurring break per project memory).\n2. **`fetch_all` concurrency cap** — no test asserts that `concurrency=N` actually bounds simultaneous in-flight requests; a regression (e.g., someone removing the `Semaphore`) wouldn't be caught by any test above.\n3. **`Store.next_seq` under real concurrency** — the `BEGIN IMMEDIATE` locking claim (used for parallel pipeline workers) is untested under actual thread/process contention; a `ThreadPoolExecutor` stress test hitting the same DB file would validate the no-duplicate-sequence guarantee.\n4. **`agent.py`'s `cmd_pdf_render`** — the Chrome subprocess invocation and PDF-magic-byte check have no test; at minimum, mock `subprocess.run` to verify the command line and the failure path (non-`%PDF` output → exit code 1, stderr tail printed).\n5. **`run_claude`/`main()` mode-word vs. flag splitting** — the logic that decides where mode words end and passthrough flags begin (`agent.py:332-336`) has edge cases (e.g., a mode word that starts with `-`) with no coverage.\n\n---\n\n**To make these runnable:** add `pytest` to a new `requirements-dev.txt` (I avoided adding `pytest-asyncio` — every async test above drives its coroutine with a plain `asyncio.run()` inside a normal `def test_...`, so no plugin is needed) and drop these files under `tests/`, plus a `conftest.py` with the `make_job` factory shown at the top. Want me to write these to disk once file-write permission is available, or would you rather I hold here?",
